### TITLE ###
NotNullNarrowsTruthyBranch
### DESCRIPTION ###
`if x != null:` should narrow x to non-null inside the then-body.
Outside the if (no else, no early exit), x falls back to int? via join.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        y = x
    z = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  z @ 4:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:9 -> int|int?

# Symbol types
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int
  z (local): int|int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NullEqualReturnsNarrowsFallthrough
### DESCRIPTION ###
Guard pattern: `if x == null: return` leaves x as non-null in the
fall-through path.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x == null:
        return
    y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 4:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:9 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NoNullableBaseTypeNoNarrowing
### DESCRIPTION ###
x is int (no nullable component); the predicate has nothing to refine.
The if/else still produces a clean join.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int):
    if x != null:
        y = x
    else:
        z = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int
  y @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  z @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:13 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): <no-type>
  x (param): int
  y (local): int
  z (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
